body:
I cannot do certain things with xunit. Eg. pass the config parameters to the base reference before any test starts. I was trying different things like [ModuleInit](https://github.com/Fody/ModuleInit) but it runs after the first base fixture starts:
For example:
**MyApp.Core.Tests**:
```
public class ServicesFixture : IDisposable
{
        public static Assembly[] Assemblies = new[] { typeof(CoreClass).Assembly };
        private readonly IServiceProvider _services;

        public ServicesFixture()
        {
            _services = new StandardServiceBuilder(Assemblies).ConfigureServices();
        }

        public IServiceProvider Services { get { return _services; } }

        public void Dispose()
        {
            if (_services is IDisposable)
                (_services as IDisposable).Dispose();
        }
}
```
**MyApp.Module1.Tests**: (has a reference to MyApp.Core.Tests)
```
// Somewhere in the code
ServicesFixture.Assemblies = new[] { typeof(CoreClass).Assembly, typeof(Module1Class).Assembly };
```
For this approach I would like to have some ability to execute a command before any test starts.

Please add a global fixture and teardown. It is easy to do I assume as many people do that by overriding the `XunitTestAssemblyRunner`.

There is one major difference between your OOTB implementation in V3

```csharp
[assembly: AssemblyFixture(typeof(DatabaseFixture))]
[assembly: AssemblyFixture(typeof(CosmosDbFixture ))]
```

and the implementation of `IAssemblyFixture<DatabaseFixture>` by https://github.com/kzu/xunit.assemblyfixture.

In v3 the DatabaseFixture and CosmosDbFixture are **always** executed (even no currently executed test needs this fixture, e.g. by filtering), but with the interface implementation `IAssemblyFixture<DatabaseFixture>` the fixture will be only executed, if at least one test is tagged with an `IAssemblyFixture<DatabaseFixture>`.

Let's assume following setup:

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        // ... initialize data in the test database ...
    }
}

public class CosmosDbFixture : IDisposable
{
    public CosmosDbFixture()
    {
        // ... initialize data in the cosmos database ...
    }
}

public class MyDatabaseTests : IAssemblyFixture<DatabaseFixture>
{
	[Fact]
	[Trait("Category", "Database")]
	[Trait("Category", "Integration")]
	public void Some_database_test()
	{
	}
}

public class MyCosmosTests : IAssemblyFixture<CosmosDbFixture >
{
	[Fact]
	[Trait("Category", "Cosmos")]
	[Trait("Category", "Integration")]
	public void Some_database_test()
	{
	}
}

public class MyUnitTests
{
	[Fact]
	[Trait("Category", "Unit")]
	public void Some_unit_test()
	{
	}
}
```

Running only unit tests with `dotnet test --filter Category=Unit` will always execute the DatabaseFixture and the CosmosDbFixture  in v3, but not with `IAssemblyFixture<DatabaseFixture>`.

Or running `dotnet test --filter Category=Database` should only run the DatabaseFixture, but not the CosmosDbFixture.

Is this somehow possible OOTB with v3?

I'm fine with executing each fixture (applied on a TestClass) , even though they are not used via constructor argument. That's not my point.

I also cannot use ICollectionFixture<>, because with that I cannot control exactly which fixture should be executed if only some tests from the collection are executed.

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        // ... initialize data in the test database ...
    }
}

public class CosmosDbFixture : IDisposable
{
    public CosmosDbFixture()
    {
        // ... initialize data in the cosmos database ...
    }
}

[CollectionDefinition("Integration Tests")] // should not run in parallel
public class IntegrationTestCollection : ICollectionFixture<DatabaseFixture>, ICollectionFixture<CosmosDbFixture>
{
    // This class has no code, and is never created. Its purpose is simply
    // to be the place to apply [CollectionDefinition] and all the
    // ICollectionFixture<> interfaces.
}

[Collection("Integration Tests")]
public class MyDatabaseTests // needs only : DatabaseFixture
{
	[Fact]
	[Trait("Category", "Database")]
	[Trait("Category", "Integration")]
	public void Some_database_test()
	{
	}
}

[Collection("Integration Tests")]
public class MyCosmosTests // needs only : CosmosDbFixture
	[Fact]
	[Trait("Category", "Cosmos")]
	[Trait("Category", "Integration")]
	public void Some_database_test()
	{
	}
}

[Collection("Integration Tests")]
public class MyDatabseAndCosmosTests // needs both: DatabaseFixture and CosmosDbFixture
{
	[Fact]
	[Trait("Category", "Cosmos")]
	[Trait("Category", "Integration")]
	public void Some_database_test()
	{
	}
}

public class MyUnitTests
{
	[Fact]
	[Trait("Category", "Unit")]
	public void Some_unit_test()
	{
	}
}
```

Running only the tests in class `MyCosmosTests` should only run the `CosmosDbFixture`.

Splitting my tests into different assemblies doesn't help too, or I have to create new assemblies for every IFixture combination.

IMHO: The implementation of KZU with `IAssemblyFixture<SomeFixture>` allows the most fine granular control of the executed fixtures.
